        args='{"final_result":"## SpaceX vs. Amazon: AI Infrastructure FCF Pressure Ratio Comparison\\n\\n### 1. Amazon FY2025 Baseline (Verified)\\n\\nThe question\'s figures are confirmed using Amazon\'s FY2025 10-K, applying the **gross capex** convention (purchases of property and equipment, before proceeds from sales/incentives) rather than the net figure in Amazon\'s non-GAAP FCF reconciliation:\\n\\n| Metric | FY2024 | FY2025 |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Net cash from operating activities (OCF) | $115,877M | $139,514M |\\n| Gross capex (purchases of P&E) | $82,999M | $131,819M |\\n| **FCF (OCF − Gross Capex)** | **$32,878M (~$32.9B)** | **$7,695M (~$7.7B)** |\\n| **Capex / OCF ratio** | 71.6% | **94.48% (~94.5%)** |\\n\\nAmazon\'s capex consumed ~94.5% of operating cash flow in FY2025, compressing FCF to just $7.7B — but FCF remained **positive**.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2. SpaceX FCF Pressure Ratio Construction\\n\\nPer the question\'s framework, I use:\\n- **Numerator:** Annualized Q1 2026 AI segment capex\\n- **Denominator:** Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA (the question\'s designated \\"primary internal cash source\\")\\n\\n**SpaceX disclosed figures (from S-1):**\\n- Q1 2026 AI capex: $7,723M → Annualized: $7,723M × 4 = **$30,892M**\\n- Q1 2026 Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA: $2,087M → Annualized: $2,087M × 4 = **$8,348M**\\n- FY2025 Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA: $7,168M\\n\\n**Constructed ratios:**\\n\\n| Basis | Annualized AI Capex | Connectivity Adj. EBITDA | Ratio | Implied \\"FCF\\" |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| Q1 2026 annualized (both) | $30,892M | $8,348M | **370.05%** | −$22,544M |\\n| Q1 2026 AI capex vs. FY2025 Connectivity EBITDA | $30,892M | $7,168M | **430.97%** | −$23,724M |\\n\\nFor additional context, if one substitutes **consolidated operating cash flow** (the GAAP cash measure actually comparable to Amazon\'s denominator) instead of Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA:\\n- Annualized Q1 2026 consolidated OCF: $1,047M × 4 = $4,188M\\n- AI capex / Consolidated OCF = $30,892M / $4,188M = **737.6%**\\n- Total capex / Consolidated OCF = $40,428M / $4,188M = **965.3%**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 3. Comparison and Assessment\\n\\n| Company | Ratio | Interpretation |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **Amazon FY2025** | Capex/OCF = **94.5%** | Capex consumed 94.5% of OCF; FCF remained positive at $7.7B |\\n| **SpaceX (Q1\'26 annualized, Connectivity EBITDA basis)** | AI Capex/Connectivity EBITDA = **370%** | AI capex alone is ~3.7× the Connectivity segment\'s Adjusted EBITDA |\\n| **SpaceX (consolidated OCF basis)** | Total Capex/OCF = **965%** | Total capex is ~9.7× consolidated operating cash flow |\\n\\n**Assessment: SpaceX\'s internal funding position for AI infrastructure is dramatically MORE constrained than Amazon\'s was in FY2025.**\\n\\n- Amazon\'s capex, while consuming 94.5% of OCF, still left **positive** free cash flow of $7.7B. Amazon funded its AI/buildout primarily from internally generated operating cash flow.\\n- SpaceX\'s AI capex alone (annualized) exceeds its Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA by ~3.7×, producing an implied \\"FCF\\" of **−$22.5B**. On a consolidated GAAP-cash basis, total capex exceeds operating cash flow by nearly 10×, with consolidated OCF of only ~$4.2B annualized against ~$40.4B annualized total capex.\\n- The S-1 confirms SpaceX is **not** funding AI infrastructure from internal cash: FY2025 financing activities included $16.1B of AI-segment debt/financing arrangements, and Q1 2026 added a $20.0B SpaceX Bridge Loan plus $7.4B in equity proceeds. SpaceX explicitly states it will \\"access a range of debt and equity financing solutions available to us as a public company to fund future investments.\\"\\n\\nIn short: Amazon stretched its internal cash generation to the limit (94.5%) but remained self-funding on a cash basis. SpaceX\'s internal cash generation covers only a small fraction of its AI capex, with the gap filled by external debt and equity — a structurally more constrained and externally dependent funding position.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 4. Disclosure Gaps and Omissions in the SpaceX S-1 That Limit Confidence\\n\\nSeveral material disclosure issues constrain the reliability of this comparison:\\n\\n1. **The S-1 does NOT explicitly label Connectivity as the \\"primary internal cash source.\\"** This is the question\'s framing, not the filing\'s language. The filing describes a historical capital-allocation cycle (\\"We invested in our Connectivity segment as we generated Segment Adjusted EBITDA from our Space segment...\\") but does not designate any single segment as the primary cash source for AI. Connectivity is the largest EBITDA contributor, but the filing does not state that its cash flow is earmarked to fund AI.\\n\\n2. **The S-1 does NOT define or disclose a \\"free cash flow\\" metric.** The Amazon comparison rests on an FCF construct; SpaceX provides no analogous non-GAAP liquidity measure. Any FCF figure for SpaceX must be derived (OCF − Capex), and the filing does not present or endorse this derivation.\\n\\n3. **Segment Adjusted EBITDA ≠ Operating Cash Flow.** Amazon\'s ratio uses GAAP operating cash flow. SpaceX\'s Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA is a non-GAAP measure that adds back depreciation & amortization, share-based compensation, restructuring, and impairments — none of which are cash-neutral. EBITDA systematically overstates cash generation relative to OCF, making the SpaceX ratio look less extreme than a true cash-based comparison. The consolidated OCF figures confirm this: Q1 2026 consolidated OCF was $1,047M vs. Connectivity Adjusted EBITDA of $2,087M (a ~50% gap), and FY2025 consolidated OCF was $6,785M vs. Connectivity Adjusted EBITDA of $7,168M.\\n\\n4. **No segment-level operating cash flow disclosure.** The filing does not break out operating cash flow by segment. We cannot isolate the actual cash generated by Connectivity (as opposed to its EBITDA), nor can we determine how much of consolidated OCF is consumed by the loss-making Space and AI segments before any cash reaches the AI capex line.\\n\\n5. **The question isolates AI capex, but SpaceX\'s total capex is far larger.** Using only AI capex ($30.9B annualized) understates total capex pressure. Total Q1 2026 capex annualized is $40.4B, which — measured against either Connectivity EBITDA or consolidated OCF — produces even more extreme ratios (484% and 965%, respectively).\\n\\n6. **Annualization of a single quarter is an assumption the filing does not endorse.** Q1 2026 capex may not be representative of the full year. The filing notes SpaceX \\"may reduce future capital expenditures in this segment and reallocate those expenditures to other segments based on business priorities,\\" implying the run-rate is discretionary, not committed.\\n\\n7. **The consolidated financials are retrospectively recast** to include xAI (merged February 2, 2026) and X Holdings (merged into xAI March 28, 2025) for all historical periods. No period reflects standalone SpaceX operations. The AI segment\'s capex and losses reflect this recast entity, complicating any trend interpretation.\\n\\n8. **No quantification of the internal-vs-external funding split for AI.** While the filing discloses aggregate debt and equity proceeds, it does not present a sources-and-uses table isolating how much AI capex was funded internally versus externally. This omission prevents a precise apples-to-apples comparison with Amazon\'s predominantly internally-funded capex.\\n\\n**Bottom line:** On every reasonable construction, SpaceX\'s AI infrastructure funding pressure ratio (370%–965% depending on denominator) vastly exceeds Amazon\'s 94.5%, and SpaceX\'s position is materially more constrained and more dependent on external capital. However, the comparison\'s confidence is limited because (a) the S-1 does not designate Connectivity as the primary internal cash source, (b) it provides no free cash flow metric, (c) Segment Adjusted EBITDA is no